T1  - Short-Sales Constraints and the Diversification Puzzle
AU  - Reed, Adam V.
AU  - Saffi, Pedro A. C.
AU  - Van Wesep, Edward D.
Y1  - 2020/05/29
PY  - 2020
DA  - 2021/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2019.3467
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2019.3467
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1159
EP  - 1182
VL  - 67
IS  - 2
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Disagreement about stock valuation, combined with short-sales constraints, can increase asset prices. We build a model showing that, so long as investor beliefs are not perfectly correlated, investors disagree less about the value of a conglomerate than about each of its individual divisions. This generates a conglomerate discount with disagreement and short-sales constraints being complementary in explaining its cross-sectional variation. We test these predictions empirically and find substantial support: conglomerates have lower differences of opinion and lower short-sales constraints than pure-play firms. Furthermore, greater differences of opinion and tighter short-sales constraints are significant predictors of valuation differences between conglomerates and pure plays.This paper was accepted by Karl Diether, finance.
AB  - Disagreement about stock valuation, combined with short-sales constraints, can increase asset prices. We build a model showing that, so long as investor beliefs are not perfectly correlated, investors disagree less about the value of a conglomerate than about each of its individual divisions. This generates a conglomerate discount with disagreement and short-sales constraints being complementary in explaining its cross-sectional variation. We test these predictions empirically and find substantial support: conglomerates have lower differences of opinion and lower short-sales constraints than pure-play firms. Furthermore, greater differences of opinion and tighter short-sales constraints are significant predictors of valuation differences between conglomerates and pure plays.This paper was accepted by Karl Diether, finance.
